Simulation of the image of a binary star with a space telescope

Let's consider an imaging system consisting of a space-based-telescope with a circular pupil and its imaging instrument being a near-infrared camera. Being space-based, the imaging system is not affected by the Earth atmosphere which results in an image quality close to the Fraunhofer diffraction equation. For a linear imaging system ie. Image(object1 + object2) = Image(object1) + Image(object2), the Point Spread Function (PSF) describes the response of a linear imaging system to a point source. In astronomy, most stars are non-resolved by single dish telescopes and can be considered as a point sources. Their observation therefore provide a direct access to the PSF of the imaging system.

The image of binary star observed through a linear imaging system can be expressed as : IBinary(x,y)=Ippsf(xxp,yyp)+Ispsf(xxs,yys)IBinary(x,y)=Ippsf(xxp,yyp)+Ispsf(xxs,yys)

where x,y are the angular coordinates expressed in arcseconds. Ip,IsIp,Is are the intensities of the primary and secondary star expressed in ADU (arbitrary units) while (xp,yo)(xp,yo) and (xs,ys)(xs,ys) are the coordinates of the two stars, also expressed in arcsecond. psf(x,y)psf(x,y) is the Point Spread Function and IbinIbin is the image of the binary stars observed through the imaging system.

In the following exercise, you'll will be provided with a set of simulated observations of binary stars with different separations, contrasts and magnitudes. You will first create an analytical model of the image of the binary in the space domain (as opposed to the Fourier domain). You will then adjust the model of the binary star to the simulated observations, retrieve the binary parameters using a non-linear minimisation algorithm and assess its goodness of fit. Finally, you'll use Markov Chain Monte Carlo algorithm to probe you model parameter space and assess the confidence interval binary star parameter and their correlation.

Let's first compute the PSF. For a circular pupil it is called the "Airy pattern" and is expressed as : psf(x,y)=I0(2J1())2psf(x,y)=I0(2J1())2 with =D(180.3600)r=D(180.3600)r and where DD is the diameter of the telescope, is the effective wavelength of the imaging system (both expressed in meters) and rr is the radial distance in the focal plane (ie. on the detector) measured in arcseconds.

We compute below, the PSF of an imaging system composed of circular telescope of diameter, D=2.40D=2.40 m, and a 64 x 64 near-infrared imaging camera with a HH band filter of effective wavelength =1.65=1.65 microns. The plate scale (or pixel scale) of the camera is 0.035 arcsecond per pixel.

#    Answer 1.a>      #

def computeImageSingleStar(I0,dx0_as,dy0_as):
    pixscale = 0.035    # arcsec par pixel
    Nx,Ny=64,64  # image size in pixel
    fcutD_asm1 = D_m/lbdEff_m * np.pi / (180*3600)

    x_as=pixscale*(np.arange(Nx) - Nx/2)[:,np.newaxis]
    y_as=pixscale*(np.arange(Ny) - Ny/2)[np.newaxis,: ]
    
    r_as=np.sqrt((x_as-dx0_as)**2 +(y_as-dy0_as)**2)
    arg = np.pi*fcutD_asm1 *r_as
    
    arg[arg==0]=1e-6 #protect against division by zero
    return I0 * ( 2*special.jv(1, arg)/arg)**2

Explanations

The resolution of the imaging device depends both on the diameter of the telescope and the wavelength of the imaging device. The angular resolution, expressed in arcseconds, is defined as R=D180.3600R=D180.3600

R=np.array([1.25,1.25,2.20])1e-6/np.array([2.4,3.6,3.6])180*3600/np.pi print('Angular resolution') for r in R: print(' %5.3f [mas]'%(r))

A telescope of 3.6 meter diameter observing at 2.20mm has a lower angular resolution than a smaller telescope of diatemeter 2.40 meter observing at 1.25 mm. It can also be noticed that the spread of the PSF of an imaging device also impacts its capacity to detect faint companions, even at large separation (see log scale cuts of the image).

def computeImageBinaryStar(params):
    I0,dx0_as,dy0_as,I1,dx1_as,dy1_as=params
    
    Im0 =computeImageSingleStar(I0,dx0_as,dy0_as)
    Im1 =computeImageSingleStar(I1,dx1_as,dy1_as)
    ImBinary = Im0+Im1
    return ImBinary

The image of the binary star is affected by both the detector readout noise and the photon noise the star.

  • The detector readout noise can be considered as a gaussian white noise with det=5det=5.

D_m = 3.60          # Diameter of the telescope
lbdEff_m = 2.20e-6  #Effective Wavelength
def compute2DResiduals(params, imageBinaryObs):
    ImBinaryModel = computeImageBinaryStar(params)
    residuals     = imageBinaryObs - ImBinaryModel
    return residuals   
    
def computeChi2(params, sigma2, ImObs):
    res = compute2DResiduals(params, ImObs)
    #hypothesis to speed up computation
    #same noise everywhere on the detector
    chi2 = np.sum(res**2/sigma2)
    return chi2

For a linear model in aa, the PDF at 2minmin2 follows a chi-square distribution with NmeasNparamsNmeasNparams degrees of freedom. It has an expectation value of NmeasNparamsNmeasNparams and a standard deviation of 2(NmeasNparams)2(NmeasNparams) (property of the chi2chi2 distribution.

The 22 computed with the true parameters is way larger than expected. The variance is underestimated in our modeling by a factor of 5.10 despite the fact that we took into account the detector readout noise. It shows that this noise model is too simple and should taken into account the photon noise of the stars.

Rem-2 : You'll analyse here the first plane/slice of the image cube.

The image of the binary star is affected by both the detector readout noise and the photon noise the star.

  • The detector readout noise can be considered as a gaussian white noise with det=5det=5.
  • The photon noise standard deviation det(i,j)=Kijdet(i,j)=Kij where KijKij is the number of counts on pixel (i,j) originating from the star.

Like in Question 3.3 (see exercise solution on moodle) we consider a varianceMap that takes into account both the detector readout noise and the photon noise of the star.

#The standard deviation is defined as the square root of the variances.
paramStd = np.sqrt(np.diag(covMat))

#It is common that the minimum reduced chi2r is  larger than one due to an 
#incorrect noise model. It is common practice to rescale the variances by the 
#reduced chi2r  (which measure an excess or a lack of variance)
#to obtain a better estimate of the parameter standard deviation-
paramStdChi2Cor = np.sqrt(chi2r * np.diag(covMat))

Question 5 - loglikelihood maximization using a MCMC

There are several Markov Chain Monte Carlo on the market each having their own Pros and Cons. We will consider here both the emcee implementation and sam, for Scaled Adaptive Metropolis implemented by J.B. Delisle.

EMCEE package

SAM

CORNER

The corner plot package is a simple visualisation tool that allows to visualise distributions and their correlations.

pip install corner

You have seen in previous classes the expression for the likelihood function.
ln(L)=N2ln(2)12ln(||)12Ni=1Nj=1(yifi(x;a))1ij(yjfj(x;a))2ln(L)=N2ln(2)12ln(||)12i=1Nj=1N(yifi(x;a))ij1(yjfj(x;a))2 where |||| is the determinant of the covariance Matrix and 11 its inverse.

The likelihood allows to model both the signal and the noise, through :

- a linear or non-linear function $f_i(\boldsymbol{x};\boldsymbol{a})$ for the _signal_.<br>
- a parametrized covariance matrix $\Sigma$ for the _noise_.<br>

In this exercise session, we will consider a diagonal covariance matrix of the observations for which an unknown additional Gaussian white noise is quadratically added to each pixel. Such a term model as a Gaussian white noise any noise present in the image that was not accounted for.

ij=20+2iijij=02+i2ij

The equation of the loglikelihood simplifies to :

ln(L)=N2ln(2)12Ni=1ln(20+2i)12Ni=1(yifi(x;a))220+2i2ln(L)=N2ln(2)12i=1Nln(02+i2)12i=1N(yifi(x;a))202+i22

def computeFlatImResiduals(params, flatImageBinaryObs):
    ImBinaryModel = computeImageBinaryStar(params)
    flatResiduals = flatImageBinaryObs - ImBinaryModel.flatten()
    return flatResiduals 
    
def computeChi2FlatIm(params, sigma2, flatImObs):
    res = computeFlatImResiduals(params, flatImObs)
    chi2 = np.sum(res**2/sigma2)
    return chi2

#######################
#                     #

# logLikelihood function for EMCEE
def logLikelihood4emcee(theta, flatImageBinaryObs):
    sigJit=theta[0]
    params=theta[1:]
    sigma2 = varianceMap.flatten() + sigJit**2
    chi2=computeChi2FlatIm(params, sigma2, flatImageBinaryObs)
    lnLike = -0.5 * chi2 - 0.5* np.sum(np.log(sigma2.flatten()))
    return lnLike

The emcee algorithm runs several "walkers" in parallel. Each walker is composed of the vectors of parameter to be adjusted. We are adjusting here 7 parameters (1 noise parameter + 6 model parameter) and we choose to use 32 walkers. If your computer is to slow, you can try to reduce the number of walker to 16.

In [34]:
import emcee
nwalkers,ndim,Niter = 32,7,500

Each walker should be initialized with a different starting value. We choose to randomly draw the initial conditions according to a normal distribution as shown below. The mean and stdev of the parameters are provided in order to gain time.

In [44]:
flatImageBinaryObs=imageOneSlice.flatten()
flatVarianceMap=varianceMap.flatten()

def logLikelihood4SAM(theta):
    sigJit=theta[0]
    params=theta[1:]
    sigma2 = flatVarianceMap + sigJit**2
    chi2=computeChi2FlatIm(params, sigma2, flatImageBinaryObs)
    lnLike = -0.5 * chi2 - 0.5* np.sum(np.log(sigma2))
    return lnLike

For initialisation, we consider a diagonal covariance matrix.
